1
00:00:06,609 --> 00:00:16,320
Good morning GDC, hi. I am supposed to remind you to turn off your noise makers, so please do

2
00:00:16,360 --> 00:00:21,025
that now. And let's get started. So, I'm going to start with a little bit of background.

3
00:00:21,897 --> 00:00:29,422
My name is Clemens Scott. I'm the co-founder of a small studio based in Vienna, in Austria,

4
00:00:29,482 --> 00:00:38,207
called Broken Rules, which was founded by these five guys. Actually, the studio itself

5
00:00:39,168 --> 00:00:39,768
was founded by...

6
00:00:41,610 --> 00:00:56,539
These three, Felix, Jan and Peter, who made a prototype of a game that was nominated for the Student Award Showcase at IGF in 2007.

7
00:00:57,960 --> 00:01:01,843
And after that they made a full game out of it and it was called And Yet It Moves.

8
00:01:02,363 --> 00:01:06,966
And it was done in 2009, which was also the time when our studio was founded.

9
00:01:07,766 --> 00:01:09,207
And a short while later...

10
00:01:10,048 --> 00:01:16,693
Martin and I joined the team and together as a team of five people we created two games.

11
00:01:17,593 --> 00:01:23,718
The first one was a Wii U launch title called Chasing Aurora and the second one was the PC

12
00:01:23,778 --> 00:01:32,144
follow-up called Secrets of Raticon that was released in 2014 I think. And now a few years later

13
00:01:34,225 --> 00:01:38,808
Felix and me are working on a game called Old Man's Journey,

14
00:01:40,570 --> 00:01:46,714
which is a game about an old man living by himself in a house on a cliff by the sea.

15
00:01:47,974 --> 00:01:55,279
And he one day receives a letter, and upon reading the letter, he just packs his stuff and starts walking.

16
00:01:56,113 --> 00:02:01,315
And as he walks, he kind of thinks back on his life,

17
00:02:02,175 --> 00:02:05,516
and players find out what happened to him

18
00:02:05,736 --> 00:02:07,476
that he ended up in this house.

19
00:02:08,636 --> 00:02:12,297
And the gameplay, or the game itself, looks like this.

20
00:02:12,797 --> 00:02:14,458
So this is the core gameplay mechanic.

21
00:02:14,658 --> 00:02:18,378
What you do is you can touch the hills and shape them.

22
00:02:19,289 --> 00:02:21,112
to create intersections between two hills

23
00:02:21,192 --> 00:02:23,034
and wherever there's a visible intersection

24
00:02:23,054 --> 00:02:24,997
between two hills, the old man can jump

25
00:02:25,237 --> 00:02:26,459
from one hill to the other.

26
00:02:29,383 --> 00:02:30,805
But when we started out with the game,

27
00:02:30,985 --> 00:02:32,006
it did not look like this.

28
00:02:32,707 --> 00:02:34,209
It looked like this.

29
00:02:35,666 --> 00:02:40,290
and we had no idea of what the visuals were going to be for that game.

30
00:02:41,271 --> 00:02:46,556
We had total creative freedom on how to develop this thing,

31
00:02:46,716 --> 00:02:50,740
which is great, but choosing a direction of a project

32
00:02:50,760 --> 00:02:55,064
that will dictate most of your wake time for the next two years

33
00:02:55,124 --> 00:02:57,566
and your financial future demands

34
00:02:57,786 --> 00:02:59,848
to be a really well-considered decision, right?

35
00:03:00,909 --> 00:03:06,171
And creative freedom is the reason that I decided to run my own studio.

36
00:03:06,551 --> 00:03:10,413
But, the more creative freedom you have, or the more freedom in general,

37
00:03:10,473 --> 00:03:13,095
the harder it is to make a choice which way to go.

38
00:03:14,375 --> 00:03:16,316
But luckily, there are tools.

39
00:03:17,097 --> 00:03:17,657
Introducing...

40
00:03:17,677 --> 00:03:19,218
The Box.

41
00:03:21,826 --> 00:03:28,628
The box really is just a metaphor for setting yourself goals based on your own constraints.

42
00:03:28,989 --> 00:03:41,894
And you can kind of use that to question or to test your own decisions or try to find answers to questions that you have about like where you're going to go and how you're...

43
00:03:42,475 --> 00:03:49,146
going to do it. So this in and on itself is not a very particularly new concept and many people use it in project

44
00:03:49,667 --> 00:03:56,197
management, but it's also one of the the cornerstones of why Oldman's journey looks like the way it does.

45
00:03:57,379 --> 00:04:01,844
And to us this has like sort of like three main ingredients

46
00:04:01,984 --> 00:04:05,929
and that is the constraints that you have

47
00:04:06,049 --> 00:04:10,214
as a game developer and the goals that you have

48
00:04:10,554 --> 00:04:12,756
for the project and sort of the strategies

49
00:04:12,997 --> 00:04:16,661
that you will sort of how you will achieve those goals.

50
00:04:17,762 --> 00:04:25,289
So when looking at the constraints of broken rules for us as a team, there are kind of like three things.

51
00:04:25,509 --> 00:04:32,615
The one is then games that we want to make, games that we are able to make, and games that currently have a market.

52
00:04:33,116 --> 00:04:34,977
And so the games that we want to make...

53
00:04:36,619 --> 00:04:42,861
are things like they push the boundaries of the medium and they offer unique experiences

54
00:04:44,262 --> 00:04:46,243
and usually are not free-to-play.

55
00:04:47,543 --> 00:04:48,824
Games that we are able to make

56
00:04:51,424 --> 00:04:59,148
often have sort of a strong aesthetic and builds believable worlds that players want to spend time in.

57
00:05:01,190 --> 00:05:06,332
And the interesting one is kind of like the third one, and especially where the overlap is.

58
00:05:06,553 --> 00:05:12,556
So, games that currently have a market do not push the boundaries of our medium, at least not too hard,

59
00:05:13,356 --> 00:05:17,098
and are also often free to play, but with exceptions.

60
00:05:18,779 --> 00:05:27,388
But the overlaps here are kind of like the unique experiences and the unique aesthetics or the high production value.

61
00:05:29,210 --> 00:05:33,074
So with these constraints in mind, Felix and I...

62
00:05:33,835 --> 00:05:37,556
set up the goals for what Old Man's Journey was going to be

63
00:05:37,716 --> 00:05:41,598
like way before we were actually like producing the game.

64
00:05:42,078 --> 00:05:44,319
When we were thinking about what are we going to do next?

65
00:05:45,599 --> 00:05:46,499
What do we want to make?

66
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:49,761
And we decided we wanted to make a premium high quality

67
00:05:50,081 --> 00:05:52,342
one time experience type of game

68
00:05:53,862 --> 00:05:57,343
that connects with players on an emotional level.

69
00:05:58,224 --> 00:06:00,045
that is not as common in games.

70
00:06:00,365 --> 00:06:02,866
In our case, our starting emotion

71
00:06:02,906 --> 00:06:04,687
was sort of the sense of wanderlust

72
00:06:04,947 --> 00:06:09,049
and wanting to travel and be somewhere else.

73
00:06:09,770 --> 00:06:13,451
And also we wanted to make a game that has mass appeal

74
00:06:13,612 --> 00:06:17,714
without compromising our own artistic integrity.

75
00:06:18,614 --> 00:06:18,794
Also,

76
00:06:23,914 --> 00:06:25,895
We wanted to make a game that is so beautiful,

77
00:06:26,035 --> 00:06:28,197
it will stick out of the mass and make editors

78
00:06:28,237 --> 00:06:29,958
want to decorate their storefronts with it,

79
00:06:30,078 --> 00:06:32,420
which means features for us, and that is good.

80
00:06:34,722 --> 00:06:37,744
We also wanted to make a game that is so accessible,

81
00:06:38,024 --> 00:06:40,866
it can be enjoyed by a widely arranged demographic

82
00:06:41,447 --> 00:06:44,429
using the simplest form of input, which is a single touch.

83
00:06:44,849 --> 00:06:46,430
So, you can move the old man

84
00:06:46,490 --> 00:06:48,612
by just pointing and clicking somewhere,

85
00:06:48,632 --> 00:06:49,933
and he will walk over there, and you can ...

86
00:06:50,438 --> 00:06:52,619
drag the hills by just touching them.

87
00:06:54,761 --> 00:06:56,502
And finally, we wanted to make a game

88
00:06:56,702 --> 00:06:58,324
for the so-called reading nook,

89
00:06:58,604 --> 00:07:01,046
so the place that you sort of retreat to,

90
00:07:01,386 --> 00:07:03,187
that where you kind of read a book

91
00:07:03,407 --> 00:07:10,733
or have kind of like no time pressure to enjoy something.

92
00:07:11,593 --> 00:07:13,114
So we decided we wanted to make a game

93
00:07:13,134 --> 00:07:16,817
that has about 19 minutes of playtime and about 15 levels.

94
00:07:18,870 --> 00:07:23,291
These were the goals, but what strategies

95
00:07:25,151 --> 00:07:31,153
were we going to use to achieve our goals?

96
00:07:31,333 --> 00:07:34,294
One of the strategies that we thought we wanted to employ

97
00:07:34,334 --> 00:07:35,514
was to tell a simple story

98
00:07:35,534 --> 00:07:38,575
that everyone can relate to only using images.

99
00:07:38,975 --> 00:07:41,516
There is no text in the game, there is no localization,

100
00:07:41,596 --> 00:07:42,336
there is no reading.

101
00:07:45,561 --> 00:07:50,345
All the story parts and the whole narrative is told through the old man's memories.

102
00:07:50,585 --> 00:07:55,769
So at the end of each level, he kind of sits down and rests and then thinks about his life.

103
00:07:56,269 --> 00:08:01,633
And then one of an image, an animated vignette like image like this is shown.

104
00:08:02,233 --> 00:08:07,597
In this case, when he was still young and he went on a road trip vacation with his

105
00:08:08,522 --> 00:08:20,426
then future wife. And the core theme of the narrative is the topic of family. So we think

106
00:08:20,526 --> 00:08:27,388
that family is a topic that everybody has some sort of connection to on an emotional level. So

107
00:08:27,809 --> 00:08:33,731
if you have family or not or whatever relation you have to your family, there's some sort of

108
00:08:34,599 --> 00:08:36,680
emotional connection to that immediately.

109
00:08:38,561 --> 00:08:44,445
So, that was the one thing. The other thing was that we decided that we wanted to align every single element,

110
00:08:44,565 --> 00:08:50,769
every choice that we make in the game, we wanted to align to a so-called emotional progression curve,

111
00:08:51,209 --> 00:08:56,772
which is an idea that we took from that game company who did that with Flower and Journey.

112
00:08:59,814 --> 00:09:03,495
emotional progression curve looks like this in our case.

113
00:09:03,535 --> 00:09:05,796
So at the bottom you see the numbers for the levels

114
00:09:06,476 --> 00:09:10,657
and the line going up and down is kind of like positive

115
00:09:10,697 --> 00:09:11,757
and negative emotions.

116
00:09:12,397 --> 00:09:15,438
And as the player progresses through the game,

117
00:09:16,779 --> 00:09:21,520
this is where sort of like the level of where we are

118
00:09:21,580 --> 00:09:23,620
in terms of positivity and negativity

119
00:09:23,701 --> 00:09:24,901
or happiness and sadness.

120
00:09:25,681 --> 00:09:27,342
either the old man experiences,

121
00:09:28,502 --> 00:09:32,805
but that is also reflected in all of the puzzle,

122
00:09:33,025 --> 00:09:38,327
game mechanics, and the interactive elements

123
00:09:38,387 --> 00:09:39,608
and basically everything else.

124
00:09:39,988 --> 00:09:41,869
So this was really useful for us

125
00:09:41,989 --> 00:09:45,171
to help pick the right environments

126
00:09:45,411 --> 00:09:47,472
and help pick the right landscapes and moods

127
00:09:47,552 --> 00:09:49,113
and colors for wherever we are.

128
00:09:49,493 --> 00:09:52,894
It helped pick prototypes, distribute different puzzles.

129
00:09:53,555 --> 00:09:55,376
and cut content if necessary,

130
00:09:55,696 --> 00:09:59,559
and it also made communicating with the team a lot easier

131
00:09:59,599 --> 00:10:03,301
because we could tell them what emotions to aim for

132
00:10:03,401 --> 00:10:04,982
for whatever they were working on.

133
00:10:08,975 --> 00:10:12,476
Finally, we also decided we wanted to build a world

134
00:10:12,556 --> 00:10:15,837
filled with whimsical details and rich interactivity.

135
00:10:15,897 --> 00:10:17,358
So there would be all these things

136
00:10:17,398 --> 00:10:20,218
that you can sort of like touch and they would react

137
00:10:20,838 --> 00:10:21,759
and something would happen.

138
00:10:23,379 --> 00:10:27,680
And lastly, which is a little bit of a no brainer in a way,

139
00:10:27,740 --> 00:10:30,401
but assemble a team of excellent collaborators.

140
00:10:30,881 --> 00:10:32,702
which I'm pointing out here because

141
00:10:33,903 --> 00:10:36,324
one of those collaborators is Salon Alpin

142
00:10:36,885 --> 00:10:40,447
and they are an animation studio that are partially based in Vienna

143
00:10:40,947 --> 00:10:42,408
at the same office as we are

144
00:10:42,748 --> 00:10:45,570
and partially based in Lisbon in Portugal

145
00:10:46,250 --> 00:10:49,932
and they are specialized on visual narrative

146
00:10:50,132 --> 00:10:53,034
so basically telling story only using imagery

147
00:10:53,715 --> 00:10:57,337
and Lipp, who is the art director of Salon Alpin

148
00:10:57,417 --> 00:10:59,038
played a very important role in

149
00:10:59,538 --> 00:11:01,519
finding the art style for Old Man's Journey.

150
00:11:02,459 --> 00:11:04,360
And that's basically it.

151
00:11:05,060 --> 00:11:08,362
This is where our box is done in a way.

152
00:11:08,382 --> 00:11:12,143
Now we have all these components that we can then use

153
00:11:12,203 --> 00:11:14,984
to inform the decisions that we were going to make

154
00:11:15,024 --> 00:11:15,705
with the art style.

155
00:11:16,285 --> 00:11:18,286
And that is a nice concept, right?

156
00:11:18,386 --> 00:11:20,427
But it still does not really explain

157
00:11:20,547 --> 00:11:22,327
how we got from this to this.

158
00:11:24,609 --> 00:11:26,431
And that is still the same level, right?

159
00:11:26,551 --> 00:11:31,737
So this was one of the is the first level in the game and it introduces the players to

160
00:11:32,638 --> 00:11:34,661
to being able to switch between hills.

161
00:11:34,761 --> 00:11:39,927
So we all we had was this pink figure and this blue kind of like target marker to tell players where to go.

162
00:11:40,748 --> 00:11:43,250
And that was that.

163
00:11:44,130 --> 00:11:46,652
And when we first only had these prototypes,

164
00:11:47,914 --> 00:11:51,016
I started, and also when our box was not yet done,

165
00:11:51,416 --> 00:11:53,458
I started making mock-ups for the game

166
00:11:53,518 --> 00:11:55,059
and testing out various things.

167
00:11:55,720 --> 00:11:58,002
And since our game, our previous game,

168
00:11:58,122 --> 00:12:00,424
have been very much based on vectors,

169
00:12:00,944 --> 00:12:02,846
it was sort of, for me, a logical step

170
00:12:03,166 --> 00:12:04,728
to do something in vectors.

171
00:12:04,748 --> 00:12:08,791
And the game was also based on these flat shaded shapes.

172
00:12:09,232 --> 00:12:12,775
And it seems like that would be a good approach

173
00:12:12,915 --> 00:12:16,278
because I came from a gameplay side of things.

174
00:12:16,458 --> 00:12:19,680
So my ideas were always informed about, you know,

175
00:12:20,401 --> 00:12:24,382
by then already worrying about things like readability and that player would know where

176
00:12:24,402 --> 00:12:31,065
they would be going. So this was another mock-up that I created and it also had the very first

177
00:12:31,165 --> 00:12:37,167
character design of the old man which was an egg-headed potato-nosed old clown with a tiny

178
00:12:37,247 --> 00:12:38,388
backpack and a jumpsuit.

179
00:12:39,188 --> 00:12:44,211
And we pretty much realized immediately that was not going to cut it.

180
00:12:44,812 --> 00:12:50,356
And so I played around with different vector designs

181
00:12:50,476 --> 00:12:56,019
and very stylized variants of this old farmer guy or something

182
00:12:56,340 --> 00:12:57,320
that could be the player.

183
00:12:58,401 --> 00:13:01,743
And we did not really know about the character of the old man by then.

184
00:13:01,823 --> 00:13:02,684
I was just kind of like...

185
00:13:03,966 --> 00:13:06,009
playing around and seeing where we could go.

186
00:13:06,730 --> 00:13:09,234
And so I kind of like did more,

187
00:13:09,594 --> 00:13:13,220
did sort of like this key art mock-up type of thing

188
00:13:13,260 --> 00:13:14,101
that looked like this.

189
00:13:14,121 --> 00:13:15,724
And it was also sort of.

190
00:13:17,540 --> 00:13:20,422
informed by concerns of the core gameplay.

191
00:13:20,482 --> 00:13:21,883
Like you could immediately read,

192
00:13:21,963 --> 00:13:25,085
okay, there are these hills and you have these intersections

193
00:13:25,245 --> 00:13:27,106
and that this is sort of like what's going on,

194
00:13:27,166 --> 00:13:30,529
but there was no real emotional hook to this whatsoever

195
00:13:30,589 --> 00:13:33,771
because intersections are not like a good.

196
00:13:34,291 --> 00:13:36,352
emotional hook for anything, probably.

197
00:13:36,992 --> 00:13:41,254
And so, we decided to hire Lip of Solo Narpin

198
00:13:41,634 --> 00:13:45,956
to come up with some concept art for the game.

199
00:13:46,377 --> 00:13:48,518
And his approach was radically different.

200
00:13:48,578 --> 00:13:51,419
So, him coming from a cinematic background,

201
00:13:51,479 --> 00:13:54,440
he did not give two cents about readability

202
00:13:54,540 --> 00:13:57,322
or gameplay or whatever that stuff was.

203
00:13:58,182 --> 00:14:00,943
He just aimed, or his approach was all about

204
00:14:01,063 --> 00:14:03,184
vibe and emotionality and textures.

205
00:14:03,925 --> 00:14:07,632
and that suited much better for what we had set out for

206
00:14:07,652 --> 00:14:11,780
and what sort of like our box was kind of like developing towards.

207
00:14:13,695 --> 00:14:17,438
And it also had the character of the old man,

208
00:14:17,498 --> 00:14:20,961
which already kind of looks like what it does right now.

209
00:14:21,301 --> 00:14:23,783
But at the same time, when he was doing that,

210
00:14:23,843 --> 00:14:26,925
we also came up, we thought about who the old man was.

211
00:14:27,426 --> 00:14:30,148
And so we came up with all these kind of character traits

212
00:14:30,268 --> 00:14:34,651
about him and the three main characters in the story.

213
00:14:35,212 --> 00:14:37,213
And we could communicate that to Lip.

214
00:14:38,675 --> 00:14:41,798
started sketching around and assembling a couple of ideas

215
00:14:42,319 --> 00:14:47,384
and came up with this design which is pretty much what he looks like in game now.

216
00:14:47,524 --> 00:14:49,787
This was pretty close to the final design.

217
00:14:50,307 --> 00:14:53,931
So, we were really happy with those results that he made but...

218
00:14:55,252 --> 00:14:59,334
We felt we needed to figure out a way how to translate that into the game.

219
00:14:59,394 --> 00:15:04,016
So we asked him to do another mock-up of something that was closer to the in-game thing.

220
00:15:04,636 --> 00:15:06,076
And he did this.

221
00:15:06,977 --> 00:15:14,380
And while we really liked, or I really liked the textures of everything, and also kind of liked the lighting,

222
00:15:15,460 --> 00:15:21,262
It was still very hard to read and there were still technical aspects about it

223
00:15:21,342 --> 00:15:24,723
where we did not know how we would implement that technically.

224
00:15:24,963 --> 00:15:32,845
This was the point where Lipp's non-existing experience in making games

225
00:15:33,225 --> 00:15:36,686
started to become a little bit of a difficulty.

226
00:15:36,746 --> 00:15:42,268
So what I did was to go back into one of our prototypes, which looked like this.

227
00:15:42,868 --> 00:15:45,150
and try to apply some of those ideas

228
00:15:45,710 --> 00:15:47,092
that he had put on the table.

229
00:15:47,472 --> 00:15:49,974
So in this case, this is a level where players learn

230
00:15:50,014 --> 00:15:52,496
that you can drop down waterfalls.

231
00:15:52,536 --> 00:15:56,760
They act like sort of like one-way downward conveyor belts

232
00:15:56,900 --> 00:15:58,281
in terms of gameplay.

233
00:15:59,022 --> 00:16:02,722
And again, I was coming from the gameplay side of things,

234
00:16:02,783 --> 00:16:05,243
but I tried to apply those ideas

235
00:16:05,503 --> 00:16:08,684
and do something more kind of like painterly and textures

236
00:16:09,004 --> 00:16:12,965
and found the results pretty mediocre

237
00:16:13,485 --> 00:16:15,165
and not very interesting.

238
00:16:15,365 --> 00:16:19,046
And I was kind of, I felt like I just couldn't pull it off

239
00:16:19,126 --> 00:16:19,867
what he was doing,

240
00:16:20,427 --> 00:16:23,087
and that my skill set just wasn't high enough.

241
00:16:23,127 --> 00:16:23,207
So...

242
00:16:25,727 --> 00:16:28,029
