00:30:50,162 --> 00:30:53,363
This is also one of the core ideas that informs the art style.

488
00:30:53,783 --> 00:30:57,284
Everything is flat and everything is stacked on top of each other.

489
00:30:57,984 --> 00:31:02,165
And there's almost no real lighting in terms of volume.

490
00:31:03,465 --> 00:31:05,765
Everything is sort of like top to bottom.

491
00:31:06,005 --> 00:31:10,086
So this is easily viewed when looking at like a single asset,

492
00:31:10,146 --> 00:31:12,027
like a generic asset, like a bush.

493
00:31:12,447 --> 00:31:17,188
So the way it works is we have this basic, clear, sort of reduced shape.

494
00:31:18,928 --> 00:31:23,009
add some darker bits, some sort of shadow on the bottom,

495
00:31:24,009 --> 00:31:26,089
a little bit of lighter bits on the top, and some details,

496
00:31:26,830 --> 00:31:30,730
and add another layer with a little bit of a color shift,

497
00:31:31,390 --> 00:31:34,711
and basically the same details, and then a third one,

498
00:31:35,211 --> 00:31:39,512
and this sort of gives you an idea of a bush, right?

499
00:31:39,592 --> 00:31:41,272
But there's no real volume, it's just like,

500
00:31:41,372 --> 00:31:43,093
boop, boop, boop, three layers, that's it.

501
00:31:46,054 --> 00:31:47,135
We thought that would work well,

502
00:31:48,095 --> 00:31:51,237
but then realized that when we put that in the game,

503
00:31:51,257 --> 00:31:54,258
we would need many different color variations of these bushes,

504
00:31:54,478 --> 00:31:56,079
and saving all those sprites,

505
00:31:56,359 --> 00:31:57,700
the same sprites in different colors,

506
00:31:58,240 --> 00:32:00,181
is not a very effective way of doing things.

507
00:32:01,002 --> 00:32:04,224
What we did was to make monochrome versions of that

508
00:32:04,424 --> 00:32:06,305
and create a shader in Unity

509
00:32:06,665 --> 00:32:11,088
that would color map two or three colors onto that sprite,

510
00:32:11,348 --> 00:32:13,649
and we could get pretty similar results with that.

511
00:32:13,769 --> 00:32:15,710
But we could also make something like this,

512
00:32:16,471 --> 00:32:18,132
or something like this if we wanted to.

513
00:32:20,033 --> 00:32:23,195
That was good, and I still had to figure out ...

514
00:32:24,429 --> 00:32:26,351
like the overall vocabulary.

515
00:32:26,531 --> 00:32:29,515
It is easy for me to break these things down right now,

516
00:32:29,595 --> 00:32:31,517
but in reality to get to this point,

517
00:32:31,557 --> 00:32:34,300
there was like a lot of experimentation involved,

518
00:32:34,360 --> 00:32:37,804
and also kind of a consulting lip from time to time.

519
00:32:39,781 --> 00:32:42,362
One time when I wanted to come up with an olive tree,

520
00:32:42,522 --> 00:32:43,822
and I really struggled with that,

521
00:32:44,062 --> 00:32:45,842
I asked Lip how he would do it.

522
00:32:46,382 --> 00:32:49,623
And he always had the idea of very strong lighting

523
00:32:49,683 --> 00:32:55,004
situations and sharp shadows and lots of volume,

524
00:32:55,104 --> 00:32:58,005
but we could not really make that work in game

525
00:32:58,045 --> 00:33:00,025
because if you have these strong lighting situations

526
00:33:00,165 --> 00:33:01,586
and you would shape a hill,

527
00:33:01,986 --> 00:33:04,806
the hill would sort of have to dynamically adapt

528
00:33:04,966 --> 00:33:05,507
to the lights.

529
00:33:06,267 --> 00:33:10,071
and that was for us just technically very hard to pull off

530
00:33:10,131 --> 00:33:13,054
and we did not even have an idea of how we would do it.

531
00:33:14,255 --> 00:33:16,677
So anyway, Lib proposed this as a tree

532
00:33:16,977 --> 00:33:18,819
and what I liked, a lot of the ideas

533
00:33:18,879 --> 00:33:20,181
and again sort of like the textures

534
00:33:20,261 --> 00:33:23,524
and especially the trunk, it had too much volume.

535
00:33:23,664 --> 00:33:25,105
So I did my own version of that

536
00:33:25,526 --> 00:33:27,328
and I sort of like broke it down again into.

537
00:33:28,449 --> 00:33:34,693
into those separate layers using these gradient-like color changes.

538
00:33:35,534 --> 00:33:38,817
And, yeah, we were really happy with how that looked.

539
00:33:38,937 --> 00:33:41,599
So we split it up into different parts,

540
00:33:41,799 --> 00:33:44,341
imported it to Unity, reassembled it there,

541
00:33:44,501 --> 00:33:47,443
added some physics, and we had bouncy trees.

542
00:33:48,384 --> 00:33:49,925
And we were happy, that was good.

543
00:33:49,945 --> 00:33:52,787
So, what about characters?

544
00:33:54,148 --> 00:33:58,350
There's the same scene at the top of the level at the hotel.

545
00:33:58,370 --> 00:34:06,555
And this is my initial sketch of a camper guy sitting there playing his guitar,

546
00:34:06,896 --> 00:34:09,037
waiting for his girlfriend to pick him up with the bus.

547
00:34:10,354 --> 00:34:16,440
And it was OK, but I didn't feel like it was according

548
00:34:16,580 --> 00:34:19,642
to the rest of the style rules that we were currently

549
00:34:19,683 --> 00:34:21,204
sort of like building and making.

550
00:34:21,684 --> 00:34:24,487
So again, I asked Lip if he could give me

551
00:34:24,527 --> 00:34:27,009
some feedback on that and maybe make another version.

552
00:34:27,109 --> 00:34:28,590
And this is what he came up with.

553
00:34:29,091 --> 00:34:31,153
And this was instantly like 500 times better.

554
00:34:33,835 --> 00:34:40,923
It had clear shapes, it had the color variants in it,

555
00:34:41,024 --> 00:34:45,709
everything was a lot more flat and easy to kind of like split into different parts and animate it,

556
00:34:46,190 --> 00:34:48,553
and it fit into the rest of the style, so it was great.

557
00:34:49,353 --> 00:34:52,557
So, let's look at environmental design.

558
00:34:54,426 --> 00:34:59,891
When we started our level designs, it usually is on paper and it's with sketches like this.

559
00:35:00,192 --> 00:35:07,919
And this is one of the later puzzles where you use sort of like these rolling wheels to break through walls to be able to continue.

560
00:35:08,780 --> 00:35:12,203
And that was the mechanical side of things.

561
00:35:13,182 --> 00:35:16,485
So then I sort of like, oh, wrong direction again,

562
00:35:16,946 --> 00:35:18,827
started sketching on top of that

563
00:35:18,947 --> 00:35:22,350
and adding like more different scenes in that whole level,

564
00:35:22,430 --> 00:35:25,793
different camera views and sort of like trying to figure out

565
00:35:25,853 --> 00:35:28,476
what the landscape would be and adding stuff here,

566
00:35:28,576 --> 00:35:30,297
adding stuff there, and then I would take

567
00:35:30,417 --> 00:35:32,099
one particular piece of that sketch

568
00:35:32,299 --> 00:35:35,522
and do a new sketch and sketch it on top of that

569
00:35:35,702 --> 00:35:36,102
and like,

570
00:35:36,883 --> 00:35:39,844
If you leave that like laying around for two days

571
00:35:39,884 --> 00:35:40,585
and you come back to it,

572
00:35:40,645 --> 00:35:43,226
you have no idea of what is going on anymore.

573
00:35:43,706 --> 00:35:45,927
So it is really important for,

574
00:35:46,027 --> 00:35:49,168
or was really important to pretty soon take those ideas

575
00:35:49,208 --> 00:35:50,949
that we thought out on paper

576
00:35:51,269 --> 00:35:55,031
and sort of make a little bit of better readable versions

577
00:35:55,311 --> 00:35:55,671
of that.

578
00:35:56,251 --> 00:35:58,172
And this is not the same level right now.

579
00:35:58,232 --> 00:36:00,793
Unfortunately, I don't have those sketches anymore,

580
00:36:01,054 --> 00:36:02,794
but it kind of like shows the principle of,

581
00:36:04,111 --> 00:36:12,838
like already on paper trying to figure out what the landscape aspects of that specific level would be and what all these hills and things could look like and

582
00:36:13,178 --> 00:36:20,664
this is the point where you start thinking about landscape itself. So of course that also means that the level design

583
00:36:21,485 --> 00:36:27,971
starts to modify a little bit because for things to work visually you have to push around some things move some things over there

584
00:36:28,451 --> 00:36:32,055
Try to keep with the stick with the same idea in the core

585
00:36:32,575 --> 00:36:33,416
level mechanic

586
00:36:34,757 --> 00:36:39,162
But make it work visually so this was always kind of like a push and pull between me and Felix who?

587
00:36:39,582 --> 00:36:46,208
Felix was the game the level designer and I am the decorator so to say who's trying to make things work visually

588
00:36:46,668 --> 00:36:49,169
And especially in the beginning where we did not really know

589
00:36:49,809 --> 00:36:51,690
which elements are going to work

590
00:36:51,750 --> 00:36:53,790
and what we're gonna put where

591
00:36:53,930 --> 00:36:57,331
and there was still like all these questions and open ends.

592
00:36:58,171 --> 00:37:00,972
This approach was a little bit more chaotic.

593
00:37:01,052 --> 00:37:04,393
So we already had puzzle prototype levels

594
00:37:04,413 --> 00:37:05,993
that already kind of like looked like this.

595
00:37:06,553 --> 00:37:08,654
And then I kind of like sketched over on that

596
00:37:08,734 --> 00:37:11,174
and then we flipped those around and put them somewhere else

597
00:37:11,254 --> 00:37:14,875
and it was a very, very iterative process in that way.

598
00:37:15,535 --> 00:37:15,675
And...

599
00:37:17,496 --> 00:37:24,101
Often what I did then was to, when trying to figure out what the environment would look like,

600
00:37:24,681 --> 00:37:29,365
was to assemble a mood board and set up a basic color scheme of where we wanted to go,

601
00:37:29,945 --> 00:37:35,790
which was informed by our emotional curve, and then kind of came up with this...

602
00:37:36,830 --> 00:37:39,992
mood mock-up sort of where we are right now,

603
00:37:40,112 --> 00:37:41,913
and then kind of like do this overview,

604
00:37:42,714 --> 00:37:44,755
simple overview and start working on textures

605
00:37:44,815 --> 00:37:46,756
and trying to bring that into the level.

606
00:37:47,776 --> 00:37:49,217
As we worked on the project,

607
00:37:49,737 --> 00:37:52,579
all those processes became more and more streamlined.

608
00:37:52,839 --> 00:37:56,661
So, later on, we already exactly knew

609
00:37:56,781 --> 00:37:58,162
which puzzles were going to where,

610
00:37:58,602 --> 00:38:00,343
we were doing a lot of play testing,

611
00:38:00,463 --> 00:38:03,305
and we already knew better what worked

612
00:38:03,385 --> 00:38:05,486
and kind of like what the difficulty curve would look like.

613
00:38:06,767 --> 00:38:14,575
So we basically kind of stitched together various puzzle prototypes to make one level.

614
00:38:15,235 --> 00:38:19,519
And this is how I'm usually doing mock-ups for a single level now.

615
00:38:20,120 --> 00:38:26,306
It's by going into the level, taking screenshots of each camera view in the level,

616
00:38:26,787 --> 00:38:28,989
and then I stitch them together in Photoshop.

617
00:38:29,829 --> 00:38:38,357
and I roughly sketch the landscape on top of that, already digitally.

618
00:38:38,998 --> 00:38:45,004
And also again in this case, we are in the middle of the level,

619
00:38:45,284 --> 00:38:47,726
so our emotional progression curve is kind of...

620
00:38:48,167 --> 00:38:53,911
dipping downwards at that moment and this is exactly what the theme of this level is.

621
00:38:54,311 --> 00:39:00,216
There are like a lot of waterfalls, you start at the top and you go downwards and the theme

622
00:39:00,476 --> 00:39:09,123
of the level is basically everything's going down. And so in terms of coloring that was also

623
00:39:09,183 --> 00:39:13,146
the idea of what we wanted to do, that we wanted to have something like a brighter

624
00:39:13,587 --> 00:39:18,450
warmer top and as you sort of like move downwards it gets more blue and cold.

625
00:39:19,730 --> 00:39:27,375
So now that I have the basic outlines I go in and put down the main sort of like diffuse colors

626
00:39:27,835 --> 00:39:35,640
and make sure that no two hills that connect anywhere have the same color so it stays readable

627
00:39:35,760 --> 00:39:40,623
once everything is rendered and then I add some more details to those diffuse colors.

628
00:39:41,744 --> 00:39:45,266
and kind of extend the color range a little bit.

629
00:39:47,027 --> 00:39:49,989
And then at this point,

630
00:39:50,109 --> 00:39:51,830
or at this previous point, by the way,

631
00:39:51,850 --> 00:39:54,171
I'm usually also adding gradients

632
00:39:54,391 --> 00:39:57,493
and those color changes from top to bottom,

633
00:39:57,553 --> 00:39:59,874
which I did not do here for some reason.

634
00:40:00,655 --> 00:40:02,916
I think it was mainly because I was going to use

635
00:40:02,936 --> 00:40:05,818
the shadow layer as sort of a ...

636
00:40:06,638 --> 00:40:11,103
consistent way to change the colors and nails.

637
00:40:11,123 --> 00:40:14,106
You can best see that sort of on the bottom two cliffs,

638
00:40:14,206 --> 00:40:18,110
left and right, the red and the sort of greenish turquoise one

639
00:40:19,351 --> 00:40:22,394
that it changes sort of from red to something more purple,

640
00:40:22,594 --> 00:40:25,057
blue, and sort of like similar on the other side.

641
00:40:25,977 --> 00:40:32,500
And so I added some sort of adjustment layer with a gradient,

642
00:40:32,760 --> 00:40:36,182
so I would get the effect from the top being more vibrant

643
00:40:36,222 --> 00:40:39,403
and warm to going something more blue and cool,

644
00:40:40,164 --> 00:40:42,945
and added a couple of trees to that,

645
00:40:43,105 --> 00:40:44,846
and basically the mock-up is done.

646
00:40:48,127 --> 00:40:50,949
From here on, we try to get this into the game.

647
00:40:51,890 --> 00:40:56,252
The way we do that is by first setting up the hill Textures

648
00:40:56,632 --> 00:40:59,434
to get most of the big color blocks,

649
00:40:59,514 --> 00:41:01,515
the big chunks into the Level

650
00:41:01,555 --> 00:41:04,517
so we see what it will look like really quickly.

651
00:41:04,897 --> 00:41:07,339
The way I do that is that I set up Textures

652
00:41:07,379 --> 00:41:09,020
that look something like this.

653
00:41:09,660 --> 00:41:12,262
So, I set up the colors, I set up the shapes,

654
00:41:13,023 --> 00:41:17,166
and what goes where, I put that as it is into the level

655
00:41:17,526 --> 00:41:20,909
to see if things work out with the curves

656
00:41:21,049 --> 00:41:23,071
and if nothing really glitches out.

657
00:41:23,351 --> 00:41:25,853
And so, I have these sort of like temp textures.

658
00:41:26,213 --> 00:41:29,676
And then I pass it on to our support artist

659
00:41:29,876 --> 00:41:32,438
who's actually mainly a character animator,

660
00:41:32,799 --> 00:41:36,362
but also doing a lot of the art and the rendering.

661
00:41:36,702 --> 00:41:37,322
And he adds.

662
00:41:37,943 --> 00:41:40,664
he does the rendering and adds all of the details

663
00:41:40,744 --> 00:41:42,305
to make it look good.

664
00:41:43,245 --> 00:41:46,927
And before that, when all those textures are,

665
00:41:47,627 --> 00:41:49,488
or most of those textures are in the level,

666
00:41:49,809 --> 00:41:51,069
it looks something like this.

667
00:41:51,089 --> 00:41:51,149
And

668
00:41:53,830 --> 00:42:01,995
Once those are in, I again go through all the camera views and take new screenshots

669
00:42:02,755 --> 00:42:10,299
and take those screenshots in 4K because our game is based on 4K resolution so it can be

670
00:42:10,339 --> 00:42:12,220
played on like a super beefy PC.

671
00:42:13,821 --> 00:42:15,841
but also it's actually a tablet game,

672
00:42:15,901 --> 00:42:18,102
so you can play it on small resolutions as well.

673
00:42:18,122 --> 00:42:20,003
But this is 4K is our base resolution.

674
00:42:20,443 --> 00:42:23,664
So I go in there and I start drawing,

675
00:42:24,045 --> 00:42:25,685
sketching the props in there

676
00:42:25,725 --> 00:42:27,246
that I would then sort of like export

677
00:42:27,326 --> 00:42:28,466
and put back into the game.

678
00:42:28,886 --> 00:42:29,026
So.

679
00:42:30,132 --> 00:42:35,815
I got this 4K screenshot and I put a single prop in there.

680
00:42:36,175 --> 00:42:42,199
And that is now also sort of obvious, but when we started out working, like trying to

681
00:42:42,239 --> 00:42:45,121
figure out how we would make our 4K pipeline work.

682
00:42:46,181 --> 00:42:52,823
We thought we had to like each texture actually had to be like 4,000 by 4,000 pixels, which is not true obviously

683
00:42:53,944 --> 00:42:54,924
so they are

684
00:42:54,944 --> 00:43:00,526
in in the appropriate size according to this specific camera view and

685
00:43:00,606 --> 00:43:05,227
Since we know what our camera views are like we can set those up in the according resolution

686
00:43:06,368 --> 00:43:11,153
If there is ever a single prop in two different camera views,

687
00:43:11,193 --> 00:43:13,416
where one is closer and one is further away,

688
00:43:13,756 --> 00:43:15,598
we usually choose the one that is closer,

689
00:43:15,939 --> 00:43:20,363
depending on how much of you actually see.

690
00:43:22,765 --> 00:43:26,028
After that, once that is set up, I again pass it on to Brian,

691
00:43:26,328 --> 00:43:29,631
who is doing the rendering, and then we put it into the game,

692
00:43:30,111 --> 00:43:33,093
and we do that with all of the stuff around that,

693
00:43:33,233 --> 00:43:34,795
and at some point, it looks like this,

694
00:43:35,155 --> 00:43:38,617
which is pretty close to what it is going to be finally.

695
00:43:40,879 --> 00:43:47,820
I also go into the level and start adding all these objects manually, like bushes and trees that

696
00:43:49,321 --> 00:43:54,162
can behave dynamically and react to what you're doing, or they sway in the wind,

697
00:43:54,322 --> 00:44:00,603
so they're separate elements. And I also add a couple of smaller rocks and details like that.

698
00:44:01,543 --> 00:44:06,504
So this is the basic process of how we build and decorate our levels.

699
00:44:07,506 --> 00:44:09,247
But obviously doing a game for mobile,

700
00:44:09,287 --> 00:44:11,409
there are technical bottlenecks.

701
00:44:12,270 --> 00:44:16,453
And these are the major three bottlenecks

702
00:44:16,573 --> 00:44:18,514
are fill rate, loading times, and file size.

703
00:44:19,015 --> 00:44:21,036
So fill rate basically is that you have

704
00:44:21,497 --> 00:44:24,439
a lot of transparent pixels on the screen.

705
00:44:24,719 --> 00:44:26,941
And the more transparent pixels you have on the screen

706
00:44:27,981 --> 00:44:30,523
overlapping each other, the more performance it will cost.

707
00:44:33,225 --> 00:44:40,832
we tried to tackle that by splitting the meshes

708
00:44:40,952 --> 00:44:42,934
into transparent and opaque parts.

709
00:44:43,695 --> 00:44:48,499
So we are using a plugin for Unity called SpriteSharp,

710
00:44:48,959 --> 00:44:49,960
which does that for us.

711
00:44:50,020 --> 00:44:52,743
It splits all the sprites in an opaque core

712
00:44:53,143 --> 00:44:53,643
and sort of a...

713
00:44:55,986 --> 00:44:57,288
an outline around that.

714
00:44:57,808 --> 00:44:59,810
And that is important because both of them

715
00:44:59,910 --> 00:45:03,273
are then added in the level as two separate game objects.

716
00:45:03,353 --> 00:45:05,575
And one is rendered with an opaque shader,

717
00:45:05,715 --> 00:45:07,536
and one is rendered with a transparent shader.

718
00:45:08,657 --> 00:45:10,759
So this basically looks like, for example,

719
00:45:10,979 --> 00:45:12,661
if you have something like a circle like this.

720
00:45:14,327 --> 00:45:16,908
In Unity, it will actually create a mesh

721
00:45:17,208 --> 00:45:20,130
that puts that texture on top that looks like this.

722
00:45:20,810 --> 00:45:26,133
And the opaque core in this case is this.

723
00:45:26,414 --> 00:45:29,575
So even if you have opaque pixels,

724
00:45:29,776 --> 00:45:31,617
but you render them with a shader

725
00:45:31,637 --> 00:45:35,239
that supports transparency, it will cost performance.

726
00:45:35,639 --> 00:45:37,860
So if you can render those with a different shader

727
00:45:37,880 --> 00:45:38,941
that is an opaque shader,

728
00:45:39,601 --> 00:45:39,841
it will...

729
00:45:41,142 --> 00:45:43,464
be a significant change in performance.

730
00:45:43,764 --> 00:45:45,185
So we have this opaque core,

731
00:45:45,545 --> 00:45:47,147
